00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:38.990
So before we get any
further, what is a bonsai?

00:06:38.990 --> 00:06:44.820
A bonsai, it can be -- the word
"bonsai" can apply to a small tree

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:46.780 position:56%
in a pot from anywhere in the world.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:48.990 position:56%
You could have a bonsai from Brazil.

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:53.320 position:56%
The reason that the museum is called
the Museum of Bonsai and Penjing is

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:55.080
that there are Chinese versions.

00:06:55.080 --> 00:06:58.900
And the original examples
were from China.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:03.660
That's something -- an art form
that the Chinese have been pursuing

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:06.220
for 1,000 years, maybe more.

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:09.820
And the word "pensai,"
"Penjing,", "bonsai,"

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:12.720
they all mean "tree in a pot."

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:14.630
So what happened was that --

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:18.840
so what it is, is the idea of
experiencing a tree small-sized.

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:22.470 position:56%
If you think about it, in the world,
in nature, we're usually smaller

00:07:22.470 --> 00:07:24.400
than the trees that we see.

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:28.800
So there's not ever a point where
you can experience the whole thing

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:30.600
at one view; you have
to look up and down,

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:32.440
or left and right, or something.

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:36.900
But a bonsai, you can
get in one fell look.

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:41.590
The other thing that it does
is it provides the illusion

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:43.320
of old, of ancient.

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.280
And I chose this example because
I think it really shows that.

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:51.190
It's a Japanese white pine, and it
comes from the island of Miyajima.

00:07:51.190 --> 00:07:53.730
And can't you just see
how it's sort of been --

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:55.680
it gives the illusion of
having been, you know,

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:59.570
leaning into the winds off
the water, you know, for eons,

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:02.500
with that thick trunk
and the chunky bark?

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:05.890
So in my mind, what this is,
it's a way of expressing --

00:08:05.890 --> 00:08:09.320
of experiencing, you
know, almost a once upon

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:11.850
at time in the Western idea.

00:08:11.850 --> 00:08:16.300 position:56%
So it's a way of experiencing a time
before, and it gives you a bridge

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:20.040
to the world that's outside of
your daily concerns, that takes you

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:24.250
out of your -- you know, sort
of the daily grind, if you will.

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:28.400
This tree has been in
training since 1879.

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:32.790 position:56%
And what we mean by "in training"
is at some point, someone, a person,

00:08:32.790 --> 00:08:36.680
chose that tree, took it either
from the wild, or from a nursery,

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:39.550
set it aside, cut away
its top root so all

00:08:39.550 --> 00:08:41.670
that was left are the feeder roots.

00:08:41.670 --> 00:08:46.310 position:56%
And from that that point on the tree
needs a person to take care of it

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:47.780
for the rest of its life.

00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:50.010
We'll all be talking about
this in our various talks,

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:52.570
but it's really one of the
great treasures about a bonsai

00:08:52.570 --> 00:08:55.020
because these trees live
for hundreds of years,

00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:58.710 position:56%
and it means that there's a constant
sequence of people who take care

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:01.000
of them through that time.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.040 position:56%
When you think about it, this living
off its feeder roots is really

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:07.840
something, because a tree in
nature could have tens of feet --

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:10.690
hundreds of feet of area of roots.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:14.700
But in -- if you look at it, this
is reduced to just a small pot.

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:19.200
And that's why it's so important
for humans to pay close attention

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:23.100
to the trees that they're caring
for when they're a bonsai.

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:24.900
The great thing about
having the bonsai Museum

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.360
at the Arboretum is you
can find large versions

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:29.070
of the small trees right outside.

00:09:29.070 --> 00:09:30.930
And here's a Japanese white pine,

00:09:30.930 --> 00:09:34.820
really at the front door
the Museum at the Arboretum.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.230
You'll walk through an
alley of cryptomeria,

00:09:38.230 --> 00:09:39.620
which is just what you
would do if you were

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:41.910
in Japan visiting a
shrine or a temple.

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:45.630
And it's, again, another way of
leaving the daily cares and worries

00:09:45.630 --> 00:09:48.170
of your life outside, in this
case, you're leaving them

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:49.810
in the grounds of the Arboretum.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.750
You enter into the museum area.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:57.050
And it gives you a chance to
kind of reflect and, you know,

00:09:57.050 --> 00:09:59.240
lose yourself in the
beauty of the moment.

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:03.070
The museum is set up in a Japanese
style to honor the gift of trees

00:10:03.070 --> 00:10:07.630
in 1976; so that was
a choice they made.

00:10:07.630 --> 00:10:10.540
The entrance, as you can
see, is a Japanese --

00:10:10.540 --> 00:10:12.470
well this is the inner
part of the museum.

00:10:12.470 --> 00:10:15.750
And like any museum, it's
set up in rooms and spaces,

00:10:15.750 --> 00:10:18.140
many of which don't
have roofs or ceilings,

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:21.470
because these are living works
of art, and they need to have --

00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:26.220
they need to experience sun, rain,
you know, snow to a certain extent.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:28.460
And most of the year, there
will be a tree on display,

00:10:28.460 --> 00:10:32.060
just as you can see this
gingko through the gate.

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:35.740
And that means that there is a
tree that the person in charge,

00:10:35.740 --> 00:10:39.650
the curator or the bonsai master,
feels is particularly noteworthy.

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:41.990
So when you go the museum,
which I hope you will,

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:45.240
do check out the tree
that's on view there.

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:49.490
So how all this started, as Mari
said, was with a gift from Japan

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:55.040
in 1976 to honor the
bicentennial of the United States.

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:58.900
But actually it started in 1975
when this picture was taken,

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:03.670 position:56%
when it shows the Japanese dignitary
handing the American ambassador

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:06.350
at the time, the paperwork
that made the gift official.

00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:09.670
And the reason it was a year in
advance is that the trees needed

00:11:09.670 --> 00:11:11.770
to be in quarantine for a year.

00:11:11.770 --> 00:11:15.110
And so this was all
happening in Tokyo in Japan.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:18.630 position:56%
The tree on view is tree number one,

00:11:18.630 --> 00:11:22.370
and the reason it was tree number
one, it's a Japanese black pine,

00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:26.200
but they thought at the time that
it had been in training since 1776,

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:29.000
which would make it the same
age as the United States.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:33.950
They found out later that it's only
been in training only since 1895.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:36.140
[Laughter] So it's -- but
it's still tree number one,

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:40.450
even though it's not as
old as the United States.

00:11:40.450 --> 00:11:44.330
There were 53 trees, and 51
for each state, and then three

00:11:44.330 --> 00:11:45.900
from the Imperial Household.

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:49.220
When the emperor and his
family learned what was afoot,

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:50.820
they wanted to be part of it.

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:53.590
So there were 50 trees from
the government and three trees

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:55.510
from the Imperial Household,
and this is one of them.

00:11:55.510 --> 00:11:57.800
It's a Japanese red pine.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:00.000
And don't you love
that zigzag trunk?

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:01.910
I think it's really extraordinary.

00:12:01.910 --> 00:12:03.210
It's one of a pair.

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:06.170
The other one is in the
Imperial Household in Japan.

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:09.990
It's been in training since 1795.

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:11.290
It's huge.

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:15.650
Bonsai can be as small as my thumb,
or more typically, about this big.

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:17.610
But they can be also as --

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:20.360
this is almost as large
as I am, maybe larger.

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:22.320
And of course, for
the Imperial Palace,

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:24.560
which has big spaces,
you'd need bigger trees.

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:27.810
But it's still smaller than if
you experienced a tree like this,

00:12:27.810 --> 00:12:33.360
particularly of that
age that -- in the wild.

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.480
So here's a funny story
about that tree.

00:12:35.480 --> 00:12:39.520
The Emperor Hirohito and his wife
came to the United States in 1975.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:42.530
And the one thing the emperor
wanted to do was visit the tree.

00:12:42.530 --> 00:12:46.600
And of course, an itinerary
for an emperor is not going

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:49.250
to include enough time to
go out to suburban Maryland,

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:51.240
which is where the
tree was in quarantine.

00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:53.140
So they had to find a way
to get the tree to him,

00:12:53.140 --> 00:12:57.200
and they had to find a way to do
it so that it wasn't going to be

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:59.560
around any other plant material.

00:12:59.560 --> 00:13:03.070
So of course, you know, getting it
into a truck is no problem, and,

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:04.370
you know, getting the truck

00:13:04.370 --> 00:13:06.530
to the White House was no
problem; but then what?

00:13:06.530 --> 00:13:11.150
Well, somehow they found either a
back staircase, or some private way

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:14.050
to get the tree up to the
Ford's private residence.

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:16.430
And that's where this picture
is taken with President

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:18.620
and Mrs. Ford meeting
with the emperor

00:13:18.620 --> 00:13:20.730
and the empress with the tree.

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:24.010
And I'd like to think that if
the -- if it was a White House --

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:26.530
if it was a Department of
Agriculture photographer,

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:28.260
their tree would be more prominent.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:32.230
[Laughter] But anyway,
it's there, it's proof,

00:13:32.230 --> 00:13:33.670
and we know that it all happened.

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:39.610
In 1975, the Japanese Suiseki
Society also gave this beautiful

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:40.910
viewing stone.

00:13:40.910 --> 00:13:45.100
And you'll find a collection of
viewing stones at the Museum.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:48.440
I bring it up just so if you go to
the Museum, you're not surprised.

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.840 position:56%
But I also think they're
associated very closely with bonsai,

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:56.180
because what these are, these are
rocks found in nature that, again,

00:13:56.180 --> 00:13:59.810
take a big idea and
show it in a small way.

00:13:59.810 --> 00:14:03.310
And there's this kind of magical
quality, for lack of a better word.

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:07.800
In this case, the crystals in the
rock look like chrysanthemums,

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:12.140
and the color of the rock
make it look like, you know,

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:14.060
a full moon night in the fall.

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:17.550 position:56%
And so if you think about it, if you
were going to have something like --

00:14:17.550 --> 00:14:21.120
experience something like this in
the wild, a garden would be huge,

00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:22.910
much bigger than a rock, this big.

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:26.090
And not only that, we're
looking at this picture in April,

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:30.540
and you wouldn't see chrysanthemums
