And a couple years ago, I had just
finished this personal project

00:32:15.610 --> 00:32:19.680 position:56%
where I had walked the entire border
of DC, the 40 or so miles sort

00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:22.160
of meeting people, photographing
people and trying to, you know,

00:32:22.160 --> 00:32:23.710
understand my city in a way.

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:26.310
And as I had finished that
up, I started to think

00:32:26.310 --> 00:32:28.280
about what's the next
thing I wanted to do?

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:31.220
And at the time I had
some frustrations

00:32:31.220 --> 00:32:32.520
with my professional work.

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:34.490
When you shoot portraits
of people, you know,

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:35.790
you want to make a connection.

00:32:35.790 --> 00:32:39.180
You want to do something
that, you know, it is --

00:32:39.180 --> 00:32:40.730
get a response out
of them, you know,

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:42.740
have them reveal something
of themselves.

00:32:42.740 --> 00:32:46.540
And what you find in
Washington often is that,

00:32:46.540 --> 00:32:47.840
you know, people are busy.

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:50.840
So often, you know, you
schedule a time you're going

00:32:50.840 --> 00:32:53.690
to photograph someone, you think
you're going to have 30 minutes,

00:32:53.690 --> 00:32:57.080
and then in one example -- and
this is the one I always come back

00:32:57.080 --> 00:32:59.990
to is I had an appointment to
photograph Mikhail Gorbachev,

00:32:59.990 --> 00:33:02.040
which I was very excited about,
I was looking forward to;

00:33:02.040 --> 00:33:04.930
we got in there three hours
early, set everything up,

00:33:04.930 --> 00:33:11.390
and then before I knew it, we
were being told that we were done.

00:33:11.390 --> 00:33:13.590
And I looked at it, I
had shot eight frames,

00:33:13.590 --> 00:33:16.720
and I had had all of
90 seconds with him.

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:19.270
[Laughter] And so I was
-- this is frustrating.

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:20.770
And so as I started to think about,

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:22.070
"What is the next thing
I want to do?

00:33:22.070 --> 00:33:24.920
What's my personal project next,"
I thought of the bonsai museum.

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:28.040
And I had known about this
collection for a long time.

00:33:28.040 --> 00:33:30.060
When I went to school
here, I used to visit it.

00:33:30.060 --> 00:33:32.720
I've had a few bonsai of my own,

00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:35.850
which have all met their
untimely demise at my hands.

00:33:35.850 --> 00:33:40.290
And so I thought about
that question.

00:33:40.290 --> 00:33:42.050
I thought, "Let me go have a look.

00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:44.980
I'm not sure what's going to
happen, but let me go out there

00:33:44.980 --> 00:33:46.990
and see what I can find."

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:51.800 position:56%
And so this first image from my book
is of the Japanese white pine that,

00:33:51.800 --> 00:33:54.150
you know, we've all
been talking about,

00:33:54.150 --> 00:33:56.800
one of the most stunning
trees in the collection.

00:33:56.800 --> 00:33:58.880
And I encourage you
-- you know, the --

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:00.360
we're not that far from
the Arboretum here.

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:02.080
It really is -- if you
haven't been there,

00:34:02.080 --> 00:34:04.270
now is a really wonderful
time to go in the spring

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:07.540
when things are starting
to bloom and blossom.

00:34:07.540 --> 00:34:12.870
And so I would go to the
Arboretum on days I wasn't working,

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:15.830
wander around for a little bit,
and try to find a tree that,

00:34:15.830 --> 00:34:17.640
you know, on that day spoke to me.

00:34:17.640 --> 00:34:21.650
And, you know, what these
trees gave me was time.

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:23.950
You know, I could spend as
much time as I want with them.

00:34:23.950 --> 00:34:26.630
I could appraise them
fully, stand before them,

00:34:26.630 --> 00:34:29.020
no constraints, no one walking out.

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:32.490
And, you know, the bonsai seemed
like the opposites of the subjects

00:34:32.490 --> 00:34:33.790
that I usually photographed.

00:34:33.790 --> 00:34:35.580
They stand before me fully
present, and, you know,

00:34:35.580 --> 00:34:39.520
their sense of time is measured in
decades, even centuries, you know,

00:34:39.520 --> 00:34:42.590
not minutes, and I love that.

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:46.260
So when I stand before these
trees, you know, I see the trees,

00:34:46.260 --> 00:34:47.880
but what I really started to see

00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:50.150
after a while were the
people behind them.

00:34:50.150 --> 00:34:52.180
Ann and Sandy have alluded to this,

00:34:52.180 --> 00:34:57.120
but these trees not self-sufficient
once they become bonsai.

00:34:57.120 --> 00:34:59.180
You know, they need
care every single day.

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:02.640
And you think about a bonsai
master who makes a tree

00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:04.820
like this his or her life's work.

00:35:04.820 --> 00:35:07.000
They put everything into this tree,

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.960
but knowing that at some point
this tree is going to outlive them;

00:35:09.960 --> 00:35:11.480
it's going to be passed
onto someone else.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:15.300
And this work of art that they
have created is now going to be

00:35:15.300 --> 00:35:16.600
in the hands of someone else.

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:18.300
And I love that there's
something very hopeful

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:19.600
to me about that, you know.

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:20.900
a belief in the future, a belief

00:35:20.900 --> 00:35:22.880
that this tree will
continue to exist past you.

00:35:22.880 --> 00:35:25.670
And also I think there's
this great sense of empathy,

00:35:25.670 --> 00:35:27.030
of letting go of your work

00:35:27.030 --> 00:35:30.530
and letting someone
else take control of it.

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:32.630
And those are the things that,
you know, as you spend time

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:34.640
with these trees, I think these
things will reveal themselves

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:35.940
to you.

00:35:35.940 --> 00:35:37.750
And so these trees became
sort of this window into all

00:35:37.750 --> 00:35:39.480
of that history, you know,

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:41.670
a connection between
events a hundred years ago

00:35:41.670 --> 00:35:46.890
and you standing right
in front of that tree.

00:35:46.890 --> 00:35:50.460
So what I was looking for was a
way in for each tree, you know,

00:35:50.460 --> 00:35:53.970
a way to sort of understand
the tree, to photograph it

00:35:53.970 --> 00:35:55.960
in a way that felt meaningful.

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:59.750
Early on, I -- you know, as I
began photographing these trees

00:35:59.750 --> 00:36:03.780
and going back and back, I had a
lot of doubts about this project.

00:36:03.780 --> 00:36:06.550
I had a lot of doubts about
the value of these photos.

00:36:06.550 --> 00:36:11.560
Part of me was concerned that this
was not so dissimilar to going

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:14.090
to a museum and taking a
photograph of a painting.

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:17.240
Like, you know, it's kind of
like a fully-formed piece of art.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:18.770
Like what would I bring to it?

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:21.700
And that was, you know, just sort
of the things that I was churning

00:36:21.700 --> 00:36:25.730
over in my head as I
began this project and,

00:36:25.730 --> 00:36:27.940
you know, kept photographing them.

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:31.150
And what I realized -- you
know, it took a long time,

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:33.810
but what I realized as I
stood before these trees is

00:36:33.810 --> 00:36:37.190
that it was not my job
to document them, per se.

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:41.300 position:56%
What really felt important to me was
to capture something of the spirit

00:36:41.300 --> 00:36:43.340
of them, what it felt
like to be near them.

00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:46.910
And this sort of little bit of a
conversation you'd have with a tree

00:36:46.910 --> 00:36:48.370
when you spend enough
time in front of it

00:36:48.370 --> 00:36:51.160
where it would reveal something
to you, you'd kind of start

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:54.510
to see the sort of invisible hands
of the bonsai masters who worked

00:36:54.510 --> 00:36:57.140
on it and all the little
decisions they made

00:36:57.140 --> 00:36:59.270 position:56%
that made the tree what it is today.

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:02.350 position:56%
And, you know, it's remarkable to
see -- when you go to the arboretum,

00:37:02.350 --> 00:37:04.450
sometimes, you can see people
working on these trees.

00:37:04.450 --> 00:37:07.170
And they make these cuts,

00:37:07.170 --> 00:37:11.470
these decisions the way they
wire the branches in anticipation

00:37:11.470 --> 00:37:14.170
of something that might not
really happen for a year,

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:16.010
five years, even ten years.

00:37:16.010 --> 00:37:19.750
And I love that scale of time
to be thinking about things

00:37:19.750 --> 00:37:22.840
in those terms, instead of sort
of the, you know, minute to minute

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:25.970
that we often live our lives.

00:37:27.130 --> 00:37:30.280
And so I kept going back to
the collection, you know,

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:32.750
as the seasons change,
the leaves emerge.

00:37:32.750 --> 00:37:34.170
This was -- this crape myrtle,

00:37:34.170 --> 00:37:37.730
I think this photo was taken
almost exactly two years ago.

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:39.620
And just to go back to
one of my original places,

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:41.700
now is a great time to visit.

00:37:41.700 --> 00:37:43.600
The leaves are just starting
to emerge on the trees,

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:45.350
and it's a really beautiful time

00:37:45.350 --> 00:37:47.840
where you can still see
the underlying, you know,

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:51.330
structure of the tree, but you can
also start to appreciate the color

00:37:51.330 --> 00:37:54.030
and the growth that they
have at this time of year.

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:57.250
So at this point, I had made about
a hundred trips to the Arboretum,

00:37:57.250 --> 00:38:00.570
and I've taken about 12,000 images.

00:38:00.570 --> 00:38:01.870
And at that point, you know,

00:38:01.870 --> 00:38:04.760
I realized that this personal
project maybe was something more

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:08.410
than just a personal project; maybe
something else could come of it.

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:10.470
And I started -- you know,
I talked with colleagues,

00:38:10.470 --> 00:38:13.450
started editing these photos
down, and realized that, you know,

00:38:13.450 --> 00:38:15.340
maybe there was a book in this.

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:17.860
And so I worked with the
designer and made this book.

00:38:17.860 --> 00:38:19.830
And, you know, when
I share this book,

00:38:19.830 --> 00:38:23.900
it's a way of me sharing my
gratitude for this place,

00:38:23.900 --> 00:38:27.990 position:56%
sharing my impression of this place,
and hopefully trying to pass on some

00:38:27.990 --> 00:38:30.250
of the gift it gave
me to other people.

00:38:30.250 --> 00:38:33.050
And I think when you look at these,
you know, trees they kind of --

00:38:33.050 --> 00:38:34.350
they speak their own language.

00:38:34.350 --> 00:38:37.750
You sort of -- I don't know, the
more time you spend with them,

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:42.430
the more you understand
where they're from.

00:38:42.430 --> 00:38:46.100
And so one of the really
great pleasures of this book,

00:38:46.100 --> 00:38:49.290
it's a book about 85 photos or so.

00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:53.360
And I was also able to go into
the archives of the Arboretum

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:58.160
of the Bonsai Museum and look and
see where these trees came from.

00:38:58.160 --> 00:39:02.180
And it's remarkable some of these
beautiful magnificent trees what

00:39:02.180 --> 00:39:04.860
humble beginnings they had.

00:39:04.860 --> 00:39:08.190 position:56%
There's a, you know, blue atlas
cedar that I think was found growing

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:10.220
in a coffee can in
the back of a nursery.

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:12.330
And it was bought for five dollars.

00:39:12.330 --> 00:39:15.490 position:56%
And another tree was found along the
side of a highway, and, you know,

00:39:15.490 --> 00:39:18.340
someone, they pulled over, grabbed
it, and, you know, with the --

00:39:18.340 --> 00:39:21.170
I think one of the gifts of a
bonsai master is to see potential,

00:39:21.170 --> 00:39:23.670
you know, see that maybe
this isn't a bonsai tree now,

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:25.480
but maybe ten years,
20 years down the road,

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:27.910
this is going to be
a magnificent tree.

00:39:27.910 --> 00:39:30.520
And so one thing I really
wanted to include in this book

00:39:30.520 --> 00:39:33.960
in the back sort of as appendix
was a little bit about this tree

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:39.120 position:56%
that I photographed, about its past,
its history, and where it came from.

00:39:39.120 --> 00:39:44.630
So I went on this image;
this image was --

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:47.720
I chose as the cover of the book.

00:39:47.720 --> 00:39:50.240
And I love this image.

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:53.320
It sort of kind of distills
to me like my favorite photos

00:39:53.320 --> 00:39:55.170
of these trees are
somewhat abstract.

00:39:55.170 --> 00:39:58.970
The trees in some ways become
something else more than just,

00:39:58.970 --> 00:40:00.310
you know, a tree, but they also --

00:40:00.310 --> 00:40:05.860
you can sort of appreciate the
ancientness of these living things.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:08.150
And one thing that was
pointed out to me that I loved

00:40:08.150 --> 00:40:11.640 position:56%
that I didn't realize at the time is
if you take the shape of this tree,

00:40:11.640 --> 00:40:14.840
the curve of it, and you
overlay it on a map of Japan,

00:40:14.840 --> 00:40:16.830
it fits almost perfectly.

00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:18.760
[Laughter] And I thought
that was just a wonderful bit

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:21.420 position:56%
of serendipity that I love about it.

00:40:21.420 --> 00:40:22.720
And so in closing, I just --

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:28.160 position:56%
I want to share something that I had
written as a foreword to this book.

00:40:28.160 --> 00:40:30.790
And I wrote, "If I'm able
to share anything of my time

00:40:30.790 --> 00:40:33.760
or on the bonsai, it is the
grace and the passage of time,

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:37.490
their peace, and the invitation
they extend to include one's self

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:39.540
in the natural order of things."

00:40:39.540 --> 00:40:41.510
Thank you.

00:40:41.510 --> 00:40:47.680
[ Applause ]

00:40:47.680 --> 00:40:52.070
&gt;&gt; Ann McClellan: So just
shifting gears just a little bit,

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:56.690
here we are back in 1972 when
Richard Nixon went to China.

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:58.640
And as you can see in the photo,

00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:00.360
there is a Penjing
in the background.

00:41:00.360 --> 00:41:04.450 position:56%
As I mentioned earlier, the practice
of Penjing, could also be called

00:41:04.450 --> 00:41:07.480
"bonsai," had been practiced
in China for thousands

00:41:07.480 --> 00:41:09.670
of years, a thousand years anyway.

00:41:09.670 --> 00:41:13.300 position:56%
And it was one of the art forms that
moved to Japan along with things

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:16.900
like calligraphy, the tea
ceremony, Zen Buddhism.

00:41:16.900 --> 00:41:21.140 position:56%
But it was continued to be practiced
in China throughout all that time.

00:41:21.140 --> 00:41:25.700
But then in more recent turbulent
history in the Chinese world,

00:41:25.700 --> 00:41:27.910
most of the specimens were lost.

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:30.810
So they are not examples of
hundreds of years old Penjing

00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:34.930
in China the way there
are of bonsai in Japan.

00:41:34.930 --> 00:41:39.380
However, you can see that in 1972
when President Nixon when to China

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:42.800
and is toasting [inaudible],
they had a Penjing in the room.

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:45.930
And I think that it -- who
knows where it came from;

00:41:45.930 --> 00:41:47.410
it was obviously important to them.

00:41:47.410 --> 00:41:50.730
I think it was used in the same way
that we used flower arrangements

00:41:50.730 --> 00:41:52.820
to adorn special occasions.

00:41:52.820 --> 00:41:55.330
And we know that Richard
Nixon was given three Penjing

00:41:55.330 --> 00:41:56.630
when he left China.

00:41:56.630 --> 00:41:59.060
We don't know what happened to
them; they're no longer existing.

00:41:59.060 --> 00:42:01.390
But the whole idea of using them

00:42:01.390 --> 00:42:05.230
as diplomatic gifts was
something the Chinese did,

00:42:05.230 --> 00:42:08.170
as well as the Japanese.

00:42:08.170 --> 00:42:12.800
So the Chinese version of
bonsai is a little different;

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:16.510
it's a little looser, slightly
less geometric, a little less --

00:42:16.510 --> 00:42:18.690
maybe in one word would
be "refined."

00:42:18.690 --> 00:42:20.650
And the other thing is it's
a little more directive.

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:24.150
As you can see in this picture,
it's a Pauper's tea tree,

00:42:24.150 --> 00:42:25.520
and there's a little figure.

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:28.490
That's a philosopher
scholar in the bottom.

00:42:28.490 --> 00:42:31.900
And so it's suggesting to you
to put yourself in the spot

00:42:31.900 --> 00:42:33.550
of the philosopher scholar.

00:42:33.550 --> 00:42:35.110
Remember, the Japanese
ones we've seen

00:42:35.110 --> 00:42:37.060
so far don't typically
have a figure,

00:42:37.060 --> 00:42:39.240
so you can use your
imagination to interact

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:40.800
with the tree as you would like.

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:42.610
But this one's a little
more directive.

00:42:42.610 --> 00:42:45.710
And I think a poem
from the 8th century

00:42:45.710 --> 00:42:48.660
in China speaks to
it, so here it goes.

00:42:48.660 --> 00:42:51.980
It's from the Chinese
poet, Wang Wei.

00:42:51.980 --> 00:42:54.400
"I sit alone in a bamboo grove,

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:57.190
strumming on my loot
while singing a song.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:00.070
In the deep forest, no
one knows I am here.

00:43:00.070 --> 00:43:02.890
Only the bright moon
comes to shine on me."

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:08.010
Don't you think that fits
with that picture; that tree?

00:43:08.010 --> 00:43:10.000
This one there is no figure.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:11.810 position:56%
But again you get that looser style.

00:43:11.810 --> 00:43:17.250 position:56%
This was styled by Dr. Woo, who was
the donor who gave the original gift

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:22.970
of Chinese Penjing that makes
the Museum Bonsai in Penjing.

00:43:22.970 --> 00:43:25.460
He was a banker in Hong Kong.

00:43:25.460 --> 00:43:29.180
He had a fabulous collection,
several museums have examples

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:31.560
of it, but we do here too.

00:43:31.560 --> 00:43:34.000
And here's an interesting thing.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:35.910
This is an image from the Freer.

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:40.200
And you can really see how the
two arts relate to each other.

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:41.500
Isn't that amazing?

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:44.910
You could just picture that
female figure easily transposed

00:43:44.910 --> 00:43:46.770
onto the tree.

00:43:46.770 --> 00:43:49.770
So it's -- while there are
connections in Japanese art,

00:43:49.770 --> 00:43:53.520
it's much stronger in Chinese
art to see this connection

00:43:53.520 --> 00:43:56.610
between the two-dimensional
and the three-dimensional.

00:43:56.610 --> 00:44:00.310
This one is a huge tray,
was designed in 2004

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:03.060
by the then director of the
Shanghai Botanical Garden.

00:44:03.060 --> 00:44:05.430
And again, you get those
old, wizened, you know,

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:09.840
gnarly-looking trees,
rocks, little figures.

00:44:09.840 --> 00:44:11.820
And here's an example.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:16.110
This happens to be on a fan,
but it's a scroll-type painting.

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:19.360
And you can see the rocks, the
trees; there's a little house.

00:44:19.360 --> 00:44:23.020
But it's the same notion.

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:26.080
Penjing doesn't have to have plant
material; it can be rocks only.

00:44:26.080 --> 00:44:29.390
Can't you just see that dragon
coming up from the Earth?

00:44:29.390 --> 00:44:31.050
[Makes Sound] [Laughter]
But it also --

00:44:31.050 --> 00:44:34.810
you have a dragon form
in plant material.

00:44:34.810 --> 00:44:38.010
Jack Sustic, the curator we've
all been talking about said this,

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:40.230
"You'd only find this in a museum."

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:43.310
And I think what he means
is this is a lot of work.

00:44:43.310 --> 00:44:46.830
And at the museum, there are people
doing bonsai all day every day,

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:48.130
seven days a week.

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:51.920
And to maintain this figure
requires that kind of constant,

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:53.220
constant care and clipping.

00:44:53.220 --> 00:44:59.390 position:56%
This was designed by Stanley Chin,
a Chinese American, who was renowned

00:44:59.390 --> 00:45:04.270 position:56%
for doing really extraordinary works
of art, and this is a great example.

00:45:04.270 --> 00:45:08.210
This is perhaps the most famous
bonsai in the collection.

00:45:08.210 --> 00:45:09.730
It's actually from North American.

00:45:09.730 --> 00:45:11.540
It's designed by John Naka.

00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:14.970
It's called "Goshen," which
means "protector of the spirit."

00:45:14.970 --> 00:45:16.400
These are Chinese junipers.

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:18.130
And where you get the
illusion of age is

00:45:18.130 --> 00:45:22.250
in the wild the trees are zapped
by lightning, which kills the tops,

00:45:22.250 --> 00:45:26.180
and then the middle part of the
foliage continues to survive.

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:29.150
There are 11 trees
in this forest grove,

00:45:29.150 --> 00:45:32.130
and one for each of
his grandchildren.

00:45:32.130 --> 00:45:36.340 position:56%
The wider ones are in the front, and
the narrower ones are in the rear.

00:45:36.340 --> 00:45:39.090
So it gives you the
illusion of great depth.

00:45:39.090 --> 00:45:43.470
So it's -- I've seen people
who just stand there, you know,

00:45:43.470 --> 00:45:46.260
mesmerized by imagining
themselves in the middle

00:45:46.260 --> 00:45:48.690
of this grove; it's
quite astonishing.

00:45:48.690 --> 00:45:51.350
Here is a picture of John Naka
with it, which I'm showing both

00:45:51.350 --> 00:45:54.470
for scale, and also
please notice the foliage.

00:45:54.470 --> 00:45:56.920
The foliage in this case --
this photo might have been taken

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:00.190
at this time of year where there's
new growth, so it's kind of,

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:03.730
you know, a little bit
scruffy, or it could be

00:46:03.730 --> 00:46:06.740
that that's how the bonsai master
in charge at the time preferred

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:11.570 position:56%
to see foliage; whereas this
picture, this bonsai master wants it

00:46:11.570 --> 00:46:14.480
to be more firm, if
you will, more solid.

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:16.650
There's nothing right or
wrong about either of these.

00:46:16.650 --> 00:46:18.560
That's just -- that's a
choice, and that's part

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:22.600
of what we've been talking about,
how these trees live for hundreds

00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:27.260 position:56%
of years, so they can -- and they're
living works of art so they change.

00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:28.680
This is one of my personal
favorites.

00:46:28.680 --> 00:46:31.950
It's a ponderosa pine
designed by Dan Robinson,

00:46:31.950 --> 00:46:36.140
a Pacific Northwestern
American bonsai artist.

00:46:36.140 --> 00:46:39.920
It was a gift from the US
Forest Service to the arboretum

00:46:39.920 --> 00:46:43.190
on the occasion of the Forest
Service's 75h anniversary.

00:46:43.190 --> 00:46:45.210
Now, what's -- there are
two things about this tree.

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:48.780
First of all, this is the view
that the artist wants you to see.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:53.260
And every bonsai has a view that
the artists wants you to see.

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:58.510
It's like, you know, Stephen taking
a photograph, that's the view.

00:46:58.510 --> 00:47:00.110
Sometimes there can be more views.

00:47:00.110 --> 00:47:07.140 position:56%
And in this case, the tree is, you
know, roundish, square-ish, biggish.

00:47:07.140 --> 00:47:10.560
And from 360 degrees,
there's something of interest.

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:13.550 position:56%
So they frequently put it on
display in a place that you can walk

00:47:13.550 --> 00:47:14.870
around and see all those views.

00:47:14.870 --> 00:47:16.470
So if you have a chance to see it,

00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:20.160
do do that because it
changes dramatically.

00:47:20.160 --> 00:47:21.460 position:56%
The other thing I love about this is

00:47:21.460 --> 00:47:25.730
to me it expresses the Western,
I don't know, character.

00:47:25.730 --> 00:47:27.030
And I could just see it's almost

00:47:27.030 --> 00:47:29.920
like a guy walking
into a bar, you know.

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:32.530 position:56%
[Makes Sound] [Laughter] And in fact
I was just out at the Arboretum.

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:35.060
The tree was on view and I
was asking how it was doing.

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:36.360
"Oh, that's tree's fine.

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:39.910 position:56%
It takes everything we throw at it."

00:47:39.910 --> 00:47:43.150
[Laughter] This one is a California
juniper designed by Harry Hirao,

00:47:43.150 --> 00:47:45.040
who is another Japanese American.

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:49.070
He and John Naka both were the
people who were among those

00:47:49.070 --> 00:47:53.950
who were very strong and promoting
bonsai as a study for people

00:47:53.950 --> 00:47:56.460
who are not Japanese and
here in the United States.

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:58.270
Harry Hirao is no longer
with us, unfortunately,

00:47:58.270 --> 00:48:01.990
but a lot of his work is at
the Huntington in Pasadena.

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:06.080
What's unusual about this tree is
the bottom looks completely dead,

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:07.380
doesn't it?

00:48:07.380 --> 00:48:10.120
I mean, you can't even believe that
there's that foliage at the top.

00:48:10.120 --> 00:48:11.840
And the lifeline, I don't
know if you can see,

00:48:11.840 --> 00:48:14.880
but there's a little brown
line just on the edge,

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:17.920
and that is where the water
and nutrients go from the base

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.180
to the foliage at the top.

00:48:20.180 --> 00:48:22.980
Now, this tree you can look at the
silhouette, and you can imagine it

00:48:22.980 --> 00:48:25.190
from the rear, it would also
be interesting; you know,

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:26.620
turned around, it would
be interesting.

00:48:26.620 --> 00:48:27.990
But if you looked at
it from the side,

00:48:27.990 --> 00:48:30.260
it would be about as
interesting as a Fig Newton.

00:48:30.260 --> 00:48:32.770
That doesn't make it less beautiful
than the one I just showed you,

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:36.030
it's just this is just
a different approach.

00:48:36.030 --> 00:48:40.220
This tree is by Vaughn Banting from
Louisiana, and it's a bald Cyprus.

00:48:40.220 --> 00:48:42.330
It started out life as
a Christmas tree shape,

00:48:42.330 --> 00:48:45.790
and over years he pruned it
and encouraged it to grow

00:48:45.790 --> 00:48:47.940
so that it would look like
an ancient bald Cyprus

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:53.600
like the one photo on the right,
with no limbs on the lower part,

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:57.270
limbs reaching up to the light on
the top, and then it has a knee.

00:48:57.270 --> 00:48:58.570
Now, what are those knees for?

00:48:58.570 --> 00:49:01.360
Well, if you think about, trees
breathe through their roots

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:03.290
in addition to their
leaves, if they have them.

00:49:03.290 --> 00:49:05.170
And if you're a bald Cyprus,
what are you going to do

00:49:05.170 --> 00:49:08.180
if your feet are, you know,
up to your ankles in water?

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:12.850 position:56%
You lift up your knee and the air
can come through the roots that way.

00:49:12.850 --> 00:49:15.270
So that's what the roots are
about, and I think it's neat

00:49:15.270 --> 00:49:18.480
that he put one into the bonsai.

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:20.110
Here's that zigzag trunk again.

00:49:20.110 --> 00:49:21.980
This is a bougainvillea.

00:49:21.980 --> 00:49:26.760
And it proves that any tree with
a woody stem can be a bonsai.

00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:30.060
The other thing I'd like to
point out about this image is

00:49:30.060 --> 00:49:35.030
that this shows clearly that the
bonsai master has put this tree

00:49:35.030 --> 00:49:36.330
on formal display.

00:49:36.330 --> 00:49:38.570
And for formal display,
it's like putting someone

00:49:38.570 --> 00:49:39.870
in their wedding clothes.

00:49:39.870 --> 00:49:42.630
You know, the trees clip to a never
do well [phonetic] and, you know,

00:49:42.630 --> 00:49:45.490
there's no little stray
little, you know, twigs,

00:49:45.490 --> 00:49:47.810
or dead pieces, or anything.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:52.240
The tipoff for when you see
a tree that's on a rocky slab

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:55.870
like this one, or if it's on a
raised tray, something like that,

00:49:55.870 --> 00:49:59.010
that's the clue that this
is on formal display.

00:49:59.010 --> 00:50:02.850 position:56%
If you see the tree is just lined up
on a counter, or even on a pedestal,

00:50:02.850 --> 00:50:05.850
but if they're not with
the rock slab or tray,

00:50:05.850 --> 00:50:09.890
that shows they're just,
you know, there to be seen.

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:14.840
Often also they will make sure that
the moss is especially beautiful

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:16.970 position:56%
for a tree that's on formal display.

00:50:16.970 --> 00:50:18.460
So when you see a tree like that,

00:50:18.460 --> 00:50:21.410
pay attention because that
means the bonsai master feels

00:50:21.410 --> 00:50:24.780
that this tree is in tiptop
shape, it's one of those minutes

00:50:24.780 --> 00:50:27.200
in its long, long life
when it's, you know,

00:50:27.200 --> 00:50:30.200
worthy of your close
attention, and he hopes that --

00:50:30.200 --> 00:50:34.110
he or she hopes that
you will take a look.

00:50:34.110 --> 00:50:36.480
So thank you very much
for coming today.

